[Because CHIKV is almost certain to become endemic in the Americas, prospective studies such as this, carried out periodically over time, would provide an interesting assessment of changes in the virus genome. It would also be interesting to determine any changes in the ability of CHIKV to infect and be transmitted by _Aedes aegypti_ from localities where the virus persists.

Is CHIK virus transmission declining in the Americas, or has the attention of the medical community become very distracted by the Zika vius outbreak? Perhaps some of both. Cooler weather in the north temperate zone has probably slowed or stopped transmission for now. Surveillance and laboratory support in tropical and subtropical areas is doubtless overwhelmed by the Zika outbreak. - Mod.TY]
